observations.recommendation:
In view of the pointed keynote areas for improvement, we recommended the following advancement measures:
a. Address the identified gap in the budgeting phase by conducting analysis on the current workloads through unloading and/or fair distribution of the tasks of the competent and technical people, who will prepare the POWs and plans and be made available during budget deliberations;
b. Establish a feedback assessment mechanism to follow through the outcomes and impacts of the delivered DF initiatives to the end-users vis-à-vis with identified baseline indicators/ targets/ objectives set beforehand.

With these deficiencies, we recommended the following:
a. Take up the following Proposed Reclassifying/Adjusting journal Entries (PRAJE/PAJEs);
b. Institute additional internal controls over the grant of cash advances for employees’ salaries and payroll. Discontinue the grant of excessive advances for the said purpose by basing advance amount on net payroll only;
c. Establish additional controls by opening and maintenance of a separate bank account for 20% Municipal Development Fund for Accountability and reporting purposes;
d. Address all the causes of non- liquidations by all accountable employees and officers. Request for write-off of the accounts proven impossible of collectability;
e. Establish additional monitoring mechanism by the LCE and Municipal Treasurer, with the latter to refrain from certifying cash availability in the Purchase Requests to support incurrence of payables at year-end in the absence of actual and available cash. The same should facilitate the transfer of funds from the GF to appropriate Trust Funds for accountability and monitoring;
f. Create Inventory Committees to timely and strategically plan the conduct of complete physical count of PPE and prepare/submit the corresponding RCPPE and IRRUP and reconciles the results of the count with the GSO and accounting records;
g. Exhaust all efforts to locate relevant data/information pertaining to the donated and disposed PPE as basis in the book recording; and
h. Maintain the PPELCs and PCs to facilitate reconciliation and fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the books.

With these audit observations, we recommended the following:
a. Immediately address the causes of all the deficiencies noted by the audit team in order to strengthen internal controls over cash receipts and disbursements, and generate reliable financial reports timely for management’s use in decision making;
b. Discontinue the granting of cash advance for payment of employees’ salaries and wages equivalent to the gross amount or in excess of the net pays of the employees and cause the immediate refund of excess cash amounting to P2,500,743.02;
c. Discontinue the use of payroll fund other than its intended purpose;
d. Establish a well-balanced personnel workload plan in the Treasury Office concerned, where there is a fair distribution and elimination of unnecessary/redundancy of workloads, with consideration that highly sensitive work and those that entail accountability shall be assigned to regular/permanent employees only and restrict accounting personnel in the maintenance and recording of transactions in the cashbooks;
e. Institute additional controls over cash receipts and disbursements by the Municipal Accounting and Treasury Office; and
f. Strictly adhere to the existing rules and regulations specifically the Local Treasury Operations (LTO) Manual

With the foregoing observations, we recommended the following measures:
a. In case of projects implemented by contract, impose liquidated damages and terminate or rescind the contracts on infrastructure projects with negative slippage of more than 10 percent arising from contractor’s fault or negligence;
b. Address the causes of the delays in the implementation of the projects in order to prevent further deprivation of the intended beneficiaries’ immediate and maximum use;
c. Cause the immediate implementation of all the on-going and not yet started PPAs; and
d. Strictly comply with the provisions of DBM-DILG JMC No. 2017-01 on the policies and guidelines on the utilization of the development fund.

Therefore, we recommend that the Municipal Accountant will do the following:
• Validate and account for the details of the unidentified CIP amounting to P8,314,449.91 by coordinating closely with other concerned department heads particularly with the Municipal Engineer;
• Make necessary adjustments to the books on identified completed projects with proper supporting documents;
• Maintain separate CIPLC on per project basis; and
• Ensure that only on-going and uncompleted projects are reflected in CIP

